What Are JPA-Specific Features in JpaRepository?

When you extend JpaRepository, you get all the basic CRUD and paging/sorting methods,
plus extra features that are only possible because of JPA (Java Persistence API) and its
underlying implementation (like Hibernate). These features are not available in the more
basic CrudRepository or PagingAndSortingRepository.

1. JPA-Specific Batch Operations

What are batch operations?

Batch operations allow you to perform actions (like saving or deleting) on multiple entities
in a single operation, rather than one at a time. This is more efficient because it reduces
the number of database calls.

How does JpaRepository support batch operations?

JpaRepository provides methods like:
saveAll(Iterable<S> entities)
deleteInBatch(Iterable<T> entities)
deleteAllInBatch()

Example: Batch Save

List<User> users = Arrays.asList(
    new User("Alice"),
    new User("Bob"),
    new User("Charlie")
);
userRepository.saveAll(users); // Saves all users in one go

Example: Batch Delete

userRepository.deleteInBatch(users); // Deletes all given users in one operation
userRepository.deleteAllInBatch();   // Deletes all users in the table in one operation

Why is this JPA-specific?
These methods use JPA’s EntityManager under the hood, which can optimize how multiple
operations are sent to the database, making them more efficient than looping and calling
save() or delete() one by one.

2. JPA-Specific Flush

What does "flush" mean?
Flushing is the process of synchronizing the current state of the persistence context (the
in-memory changes you’ve made to your entities) with the database.

By default, JPA flushes changes at the end of a transaction (when you commit).
Sometimes, you want to force these changes to be written to the database immediately—this is
where flush() comes in.

How does JpaRepository support flush?

flush(): Forces all pending changes to be written to the database right now.
saveAndFlush(entity): Saves the entity and immediately flushes changes.

Example: Using flush

User user = new User("David");
userRepository.save(user);
// At this point, the user may not be in the database yet (still in memory)

userRepository.flush(); // Now, the user is definitely saved in the database

Example: saveAndFlush

User user = new User("Eve");
userRepository.saveAndFlush(user); // Saves and flushes immediately

Why is this JPA-specific?
Flushing is a concept from JPA’s EntityManager. It gives you fine-grained control over when
your changes are actually persisted to the database, which can be important for certain
business logic or performance tuning.

